  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a financial crime that involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). The legal definitions of money laundering vary by jurisdiction, but they generally encompass several key elements. Below are some common aspects and definitions from major legal frameworks:\n\n### United States\nIn the U.S., money laundering is defined under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. The primary statutes are found in **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**:\n\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits individuals from engaging in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activities with the intent to promote the carrying on of specified unlawful activity, to conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds, or to avoid a transaction reporting requirement under state or federal law.\n  \n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits individuals from knowingly engaging or attempting to engage in a monetary transaction in criminally derived property of a value greater than $10,000, where the property is derived from specified unlawful activity.\n\n### European Union\nIn the EU, money laundering is primarily addressed under the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**, most recently the **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**:\n\n- **6AMLD**: Defines money laundering as the conversion or transfer of property, knowing that such property is derived from criminal activity, for the purpose of concealing or disguising the illicit origin of the property or of assisting any person who is involved in the commission of such activity to evade the legal consequences of that action.\n\n### United Kingdom\nIn the UK, the primary legislation governing money laundering is the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**:\n\n- **Section 327**: Prohibits the concealment, disguise, conversion, transfer, or removal of criminal property from England and Wales, Scotland, or Northern Ireland.\n  \n- **Section 328**: Prohibits entering into or becoming concerned in an arrangement which facilitates the acquisition, retention, use, or control of criminal property by or on behalf of another person.\n  \n- **Section 329**: Prohibits the acquisition, use, or possession of criminal property.\n\n### International Framework\nThe **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** provides international standards for combating money laundering. According to the FATF, money laundering typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the source of funds through a series of transactions and bookkeeping tricks.\n3. **Integration**: Reintegrating the laundered funds into the economy as legitimate assets.\n\n### Common Elements Across Jurisdictions\nWhile the specifics may vary, most legal definitions of money laundering include:\n- The involvement of funds derived from criminal activity.\n- The intent to conceal the illicit origin of the funds.\n- Transactions designed to legitimize the appearance of the funds.\n\nUnderstanding these definitions is crucial for compliance and enforcement efforts aimed at preventing the exploitation of financial systems for criminal purposes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
